## Constexpr if statements

In earlier lessons you learned that `if` statements choose a branch at **runtime** — after the program is already running. C++17 introduced `if constexpr`, which makes that choice at **compile time** instead. The branch that isn't chosen is completely discarded before your program ever runs.

### Why it matters

Sometimes you want to write code that behaves differently depending on a compile-time property — such as the size of a type or the value of a `constexpr` variable. With a regular `if`, both branches must be valid C++ even if one can never execute. `if constexpr` tells the compiler: "only compile the branch whose condition is true; throw the other one away."

### Syntax

```cpp
#include <iostream>

int main() {
    constexpr int version = 2;

    if constexpr (version == 1) {
        std::cout << "Running version 1 logic\n";
    } else if constexpr (version == 2) {
        std::cout << "Running version 2 logic\n";
    } else {
        std::cout << "Unknown version\n";
    }
}
// Output: Running version 2 logic
```

Because `version` is `constexpr`, the compiler knows at compile time that only the `version == 2` branch will ever run. The other branches are discarded entirely.

### The condition must be a constant expression

The condition in `if constexpr` must be evaluable at compile time — a `constexpr` variable, a `sizeof` expression, or another compile-time value. You cannot use a runtime variable (like a function parameter that isn't `constexpr`) as the condition. This is stricter than a regular `if` from the previous lessons, but that strictness is what lets the compiler prune dead branches safely.

### Using `sizeof` in `if constexpr`

`sizeof` is always a compile-time expression, making it a natural fit:

```cpp
#include <iostream>

void describeInt() {
    if constexpr (sizeof(int) == 4) {
        std::cout << "int is 4 bytes\n";
    } else {
        std::cout << "int is not 4 bytes\n";
    }
}
```

### Compared to regular `if`

| | `if` | `if constexpr` |
|---|---|---|
| Branch selection | Runtime | Compile time |
| Unused branch compiled | Yes | No |
| Condition type | Any bool expression | Must be a constant expression |

### Key takeaway

`if constexpr` is not a replacement for ordinary `if` in everyday code — use it when you need compile-time branching based on `constexpr` values, `sizeof`, or other compile-time constants. You will see it used heavily with templates in Chapter 11, but for now the important thing is understanding that C++ can choose branches at compile time, not just runtime.

